The most important thing in fact.<br>
Here is how we do raid instructions, and how to avoid confusion:<br>
<br>
In general always use /gu for all talking.  This way we know it is a guild member talking, and we do not spam the zone.<br>
<br>
Never move unless the raid leader says to move.  Period.  Ever.  I can not stress this enough, unless the Raid leader says to move in /gu, stay put.  If you are not the Raid Leader, avoid making any comments in /gu about moving.  Never tell the raid to move, this creates confusion and can kill a raid.<br>
<br>
Avoid being impatient and making comments in /gu about hurrying up, moving it and so on.  A raid takes time in most cases, and the added spam makes it harder to do things.<br>
Leading a raid is a very intense information job, the less added spam, the better.<br>
<br>
Never countermand instructions on who and what to kill when the raid is engaged.  I have seen this happening, this must stop at once!  For example a mob needed for a quest has agro'ed for some reason, the Raid leader says " do not kill %t! ".  Two seconds later someone pipes in: " naw, we can take it, kill %t"  The first time this happens, I will /tell you a warning, the second time this happens, you will be sent to the nearest port circle.<br>
<br>
General Spam should be avoided.  This means avoid using "cleaver" e-motes over and over again, inta-click items, and any other unnecessary action that will cause spam.  There is enough spell and other activity going on with 30  people all in the same area, no more is needed.  Extra will cause folks to miss important info and add to lag.  Avoid it.<br>
<br>
When ordered to camp during a raid by the Raid Leader, camp.  Do not wait around to see if things will be ok, camp.  Do not think you will be ok because you are a nice person, camp.  Camping avoids wipe outs.  Camping promptly means the raid will move forward.  Not camping can kill the whole evening due to unnecessary CR.  After you have camped, log onto your guilded alt, NOT onto your main.  Check to see if it is clear to return.  Once it is, log back in.  If things are really hitting the fan fast, make sure that a cleric gets out.  Nothing is more important then this when a raid needs to camp.  If you are not a cleric, do what you can to make sure that the cleric can make it out, then worry about yourself.  A cleric camped out will make or break a raid most times.<br>
